\section{The Division Algorithm}

\begin{thm}[Division Algorithm] \label{thm2.1}
Let $a,b$ be integers with $b \geq 1$. There exists unique integers $q,r$ satisfying \index{Division Algorithm}
$$a = qb + r,$$
where $0 \leq r < b$. The integers $q$ and $r$ are respectively called the {\bf quotient} \index{quotient} and {\bf remainder} \index{remainder} of $a$ divided by $b$, or the division of $a$ by $b$.
\end{thm}

\begin{proof}
Let $S = \{ a-xb \ : \ x \in \mathbb{ZZ}, \ a-xb \geq 0 \}$. The set $S$ is a non-empty set of non-negative integers because if $x \leq -|a|$, then $a-xb \in S$. By the Well-Ordering Principle, $S$ contains a smallest member, say $r$. By the definition of $S$, there is an integer $q$ for which $r = a-qb$, or $a = qb + r$. Furthermore, $r < b$, because if $r \geq b$, then
$$a-(q+1)b = a-qb-b = r-b \geq 0,$$
which implies that $r-b = a-(q+1)b \in S$, contradicting the minimality of $r=a-qb \in S$.

We now show that the integers $q,r$ with the given property are unique. Suppose that
$$a = qb + r = q_1b + r_1,$$
where $q,q_1,r,r_1$ are integers, $0 \leq r < b$, and $0 \leq r_1 < b$. Since $b \geq 1$, $0 \leq |r-r_1| < b$ and
$$|r-r_1| = b|q-q_1|,$$
it must follow that $|r-r_1| = |q-q_1| = 0$, and so $r=r_1$, $q=q_1$. 
\end{proof}

\noindent
A more general version of the Division Algorithm is obtained by replacing the condition $b \geq 1$ with the condition that $b \neq 0$, and then insisting simply that $0 \leq r < |b|$.

\begin{cor} \label{cor2.2}
Let $a,b$ be integers with $b \neq 0$. There exists unique integers $q,r$ satisfying \index{Division Algorithm!general version of}
$$a = qb + r,$$
where $0 \leq r < |b|$. We also call the integers $q$ and $r$ the {\bf quotient} and {\bf remainder} of $a$ divided by $b$, or the division of $a$ by $b$.
\end{cor}

\begin{proof}
It suffices to consider the case $b \leq -1$. Since $|b| \geq 1$, we apply the Division Algorithm (Theorem \ref{thm2.1}) to obtain unique integers $q,r$ satisfying $a = q|b| + r$, where $0 \leq r < |b|$. If we let $q' = -q$, then $a = q'b + r$. The uniqueness of $q',r$ in the equation $a = q'b + r$ follows from the uniqueness of $q,r$ in the equation $a = q|b| + r$.
\end{proof}

\noindent
We shall term both Theorem \ref{thm2.1} and Corollary \ref{cor2.2} the {\bf Division Algorithm}.

\small
\begin{ex}
We apply the Division Algorithm to several examples.
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{c|c|c|c}
$a$ divided by $b$ & Division Algorithm yields & Quotient & Remainder \\
\hline 
1 divided by 5 & $1 = 0(5) + 1$ & 0 & 1 \\
$-3$ divided by 7 & $-3 = (-1)(7) + 4$ & $-1$ & 4 \\
0 divided by 9 & $0 = 0(9) + 0$ & 0 & 0 \\
6 divided by 4 & $6 = 1(4) + 2$ & 1 & 2 \\
15 divided by 3 & $15 = 5(3) + 0$ & 5 & 0 \\
15 divided by 5 & $15 = 3(5) + 0$ & 3 & 0 \\
$-29$ divided by 7 & $-29 = (-5)(7) + 6$ & $-5$ & 6 \\
8 divided by $-3$ & $8 = (-2)(-3) + 2$ & $-2$ & 2 \\
$-21$ divided by $-4$ & $-21 = 6(-4) + 3$ & 6 & 3  
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\end{ex}
\normalsize

\noindent
An integer that leaves a remainder of 0 upon division by 2 is termed {\bf even}, \index{even integer} while an integer that leaves a remainder of 1 upon division by 2 is termed {\bf odd}. \index{odd integer} Thus, an even integer can always be written in the form $2k$ for some integer $k$, while an odd integer can always be written in the form $2k+1$ for some integer $k$.

\bigskip

\noindent
The next result should be something that everyone knows.

\begin{pro} \label{pro1.3.3}
The sum or product of even or odd integers obey the following rules.
\begin{enumerate}
\item even $+$ even $=$ even, even $+$ odd $=$ odd, odd $+$ odd $=$ even.
\item even $\cdot$ even $=$ even, even $\cdot$ odd $=$ even, odd $\cdot$ odd $=$ odd.
\end{enumerate}
\end{pro}

\small
\begin{ex}
The square of any integer can be written in the form $4k$ or $4k+1$ for some integer $k$.
\end{ex}

\begin{proof}
If $n$ is even, then $n=2k$ for some $k$, and so $n^2 = 4(k^2)$. If $n$ is odd, then $n=2k+1$ for some $k$, and so $n^2 = (2k+1)^2 = 4k^2 + 4k + 1 = 4(k^2+k)+1$. 
\end{proof}
\normalsize

\noindent
The above result can be further refined.

\small
\begin{ex}
The square of any even number can be written in the form $16k$ or $16k+4$ for some integer $k$.
\end{ex}

\begin{proof}
Let $n$ be an even integer. Then $n = 2m$ for some integer $m$, so $n^2 = 4m^2$. The integer $m$ itself can be either even or odd. If $m$ is even, then $m=2k$ for some $k$, and so $n^2 = 4(2k)^2 = 16k$. If $m$ is odd, then $m=2k+1$ for some $k$, and so $n^2 = 4(2k+1)^2 = 16k^2 + 16k + 4 = 16(k^2+k)+4$.
\end{proof}
\normalsize

\small
\begin{ex} \label{ex1.3.7}
The square of any odd number can be written in the form $8k+1$ for some integer $k$.
\end{ex}

\begin{proof}
Let $n$ be an odd integer. Then $n = 2m+1$ for some integer $m$, so $n^2 = 4m^2+4m+1$. If $m$ is even, then $m=2k$ for some $k$, and so $n^2 = 4(2k)^2 + 4(2k) + 1 = 8(2k^2 + k)+1$. If $m$ is odd, then $m=2k+1$ for some $k$, and so $n^2 = 4(2k+1)^2 + 4(2k+1) + 1 = 16k^2 + 24k + 9 = 8(2k^2+3k+1)+1$.
\end{proof}
\normalsize

\noindent
The Division Algorithm can be used to produce a plethora of results along a similar vein.

\small
\begin{ex}
The square of any integer is either of the form $3k$ or $3k+1$.
\end{ex}

\begin{proof}
By the Division Algorithm, any integer $n$ is of the form $3m$, $3m+1$, or $3m+2$. In the first case, $n^2 = 9m^2 = 3(3m^2)$. In the second case, $n^2 = (3m+1)^2 = 9m^2 + 6m + 1 = 3(3m^2 + 2m)+1$. In the third case, $n^2 = (3m+2)^2 = 9m^2 + 12m + 4 = 3(3m^2 + 4m + 1)+1$.
\end{proof}
\normalsize

\small
\begin{ex}
The square of any integer is of the form $5k$, $5k+1$, or $5k+4$.
\end{ex}

\begin{proof}
By the Division Algorithm, any integer $n$ is of the form $5m$, $5m+1$, $5m+2$, $5m+3$, or $5m+4$. We reach the conclusion by examining each of the cases
\begin{align*}
(5m)^2   &= 25m^2 = 5(5m^2), \\
(5m+1)^2 &= 25m^2 + 10m + 1 = 5(5m^2 + 2m) + 1, \\
(5m+2)^2 &= 25m^2 + 20m + 4 = 5(5m^2 + 4m) + 4, \\
(5m+3)^2 &= 25m^2 + 30m + 9 = 5(5m^2 + 6m + 1) + 4, \\
(5m+4)^2 &= 25m^2 + 40m + 16 = 5(5m^2 + 8m + 3) + 1.
\end{align*}
\end{proof}
\normalsize

\small
\begin{ex}
For any integer $n$, $n(n^2 + 2)/3$ is also an integer.
\end{ex}

\begin{proof}
By the Division Algorithm, any integer $n$ is of the form $3m$, $3m+1$, or $3m+2$. In the first case,
$$\frac{1}{3} n(n^2 + 2) = \frac{1}{3} (3m)(9m^2 + 2) = m(9m^2+2),$$
which is clearly also an integer. In the second case,
$$\frac{1}{3} n(n^2 + 2) = \frac{1}{3} (3m+1)(9m^2 + 6m + 3) = (3m+1)(3m^2+2m+1),$$
and in the third case,
$$\frac{1}{3} n(n^2 + 2) = \frac{1}{3} (3m+2)(9m^2 + 12m + 6) = (3m+2)(3m^2+4m+2).$$
\end{proof}
\normalsize

